Also had weakness and tingling. Tingling was "everywhere".. Went to ER. Treated in the ER and released. Also on this day she had additional reaction to prednisone and she found out she is allergic to this. On 12/31/2020 she had to return to ER. She was at work and not feeling the greatest. Feeling light headed on and off. Continued to work and while driving home felt confused and light headed and called co workers. Felt weak again.. Called co workers who work for ambulance service They came and checked her out and her B/P was high and having PVC's per the heart monitor Transported to ER per the ambulance. 1/1/2021 she is feeling better. Received fluids last night. ER felt it was due to receiving vaccine and then additional allergic reaction to prednisone.

Had a low grade fever 100.6 for a few hours. Tylenol taken ATC. Thursday night- no fever, headaches or fatigue but injection site cont'd to be red hot and swollen- cellutlits looking saw my PCP (wednesday prior to fever) who agreed it was a localized reaction with adverse events. Discussed with my physician at work on thursday night who stated it was a cellulitic localized reaction. fri morning- injection site improving- remains swollen, slightly itchy. less red and less warm to the touch. Beginning to form a bruise.

26 2021-01-10 injected limb mobility decreased, fall At the time of vaccination, a burning sensation was felt immediately upon injection. The person who ... Read more
Close
At the time of vaccination, a burning sensation was felt immediately upon injection. The person who injected the vaccine proceeded to flick the plastic tubing of the syringe while it was still in my arm, escalating the burning sensation. I let the tech know about the burning and he claimed it could be a side effect of the medication and that I would be fine. I did not suffer any medication related side effects. Left arm stiffness began about two hours after vaccination and after nearly 3 hours, I was completely unable to move my arm. Loss of shoulder posture, complete arm/hand weakness and extreme arm soreness were reported for nearly 5 days. Numbness from the injection site down to the elbow is intermittent currently. Tingling down from the shoulder joint to the fingers is constant when arm is laterally raised or when overused. The left arm is still having trouble externally/internally rotating/raising above my head, and while lifting heavy objects. I'm in the process of starting physical therapy/occupational therapy to regain normal strength and functioning without the tingling or pain. An audible clicking noise is noted that was not there previously to the injection. I am unable to exercise normally and have been functioning at a decreased work and paperwork pace at my job as a nuclear stress technician. I have also been losing days of time at work due to various doctor's appointments and diagnostic tests needed to identify the problem.

26 2021-01-11 dizziness Patient is a 26-year-old female who presents today with symptoms including migraine, "brain fog", fa... Read more
Close
Patient is a 26-year-old female who presents today with symptoms including migraine, "brain fog", fatigue, low grade fevers, and dizziness that began 6 days ago following receiving her first dose of COVID-19 vaccine. Pt. States she was tested for COVID 3 days prior to vaccine and this was negative. Pt. Says she had been sick for 6-7 days prior to taking vaccine and believes her immune system might of been weak from this. She received Moderna COVID vaccine at hospital. Her symptoms were more persistent and with more intensity for the first 3-4 days but now the symptoms are more "off and on." Her headache is posterior and the dizziness is also "more intermittent than before." Her headache is rated 4/10 at this time. She has taken OTC NSAIDS without much relief. The "dizziness" seems to occur randomly and is not aggravated by rapid positional changes. She does ingest moderate amounts of caffeine to boost her energy level while at work. She denies visual changes/focal weakness/discoordination/nausea/vomiting/abd pain/shortness of breath/wheezing. Pt. Reports that she has been very concerned about making sure she takes the right measures to help prevent getting COVID infection. She has researched the COVID vaccines, how they are made, and which are "more potent."

Within 1 hour of receiving the vaccine the patient developed asthma symptoms,dizziness, tingling in mouth and swollen tongue. She presented at a walk-in clinic and received Epi-Pen 0.3mg, Solu-Medrol and Benadryl, while there she received 2 additional doses and was transferred to the nearest ED by ambulance. At the ED she received a 4th dose of Epi-Pen 0.3mg and albuterol and DuoNeb treatments. She was admitted for observation. She went home and needed to return within 24 hours to the ED because her lips and tongue started to swell and she turned blue. She subsequently needed 3 additional doses of Epi-Pen over the next 24-48 hours. She has been on Benadryl 50mg every 6 hours and Famodine 20mg until present.

26 2021-01-25 mobility decreased, vertigo, dizziness I am not sure if the event that happened Sunday was directly related to the vaccine at all since it ... Read more
Close
I am not sure if the event that happened Sunday was directly related to the vaccine at all since it happened two days later, or if it was just a coincidence, or if the vaccine was just a physical stimulus trigger. I just wanted to let you know just in case! But out of nowhere, I had an episode (never had it before) where I can only describe it as what it might feel like to be drugged. I was delirious, confused, disoriented, dizzy. I wasn't able to leave bed without the room spinning. I had chest tightness and headache. When I would close my eyes, I would feel such head pressure that it felt like my body was on a boat during a tsunami. I would feel shaking and spinning inside my head. I never felt anything like it before. I was struggling to stay conscious. In the moment, I remember wondering if it was a brain aneurysm or if I was dying. I was scared, felt like I needed to call for help, but I was unable to. I allowed myself to fall asleep/lose consciousness (not sure which), and when I woke up an hour or so later, I felt a little better. I was still a bit confused on what happened and felt physically weak, but the episode had resolved. Hours later, I called the on-call service at my doctor's office because I couldn't shake the feeling that something wasn't right. She instructed me to go to the emergency room. By the time I got to the emergency room and got seen, this was a good 8-9 hours or so after the episode occurred. The PA-C at the ER ran bloodwork and a uranalysis (I do not know what he tested for since I was not given the results), as well as had me hooked up to a heart monitor. He said everything looked normal and that he would not run a CT scan since he did not think I had an aneurysm or anything indicating the need to expose me to radiation to perform a CT. I asked for an EEG and he said they do not do that at the emergency room. He discharged me to follow up with my PCP. While in the ER, I would have episodes of staring blankly into space at random, uncontrollably, and for an undetermined amount of time. I told the doctor, and he wasn't concerned. Yesterday (01/25/2021) I met with my PCP via telehealth and explained everything. He thinks it could have been my previously-diagnosed conversion disorder; however, I have not had that manifestation of it in the past. I expressed to him that I am very scared to get the second dose of the vaccine since I do not know if this event is related or not, and I do not want to die. I have two cats who need me! He did not think it was related to the vaccine, since it happened two days after the injection. But conversion disorder comes on with physical/mental/emotional trauma/stimuli. For the most part, I was feeling okay mentally. The vaccine was the only change to my normal routine. My previous conversion disorder effect was the loss/difficulty of the ability to swallow. I have not had an episode of that in years. The symptoms I experienced seem to be possible manifestations of the disorder when I did some research, but it does not fully explain what I experienced. I asked for a referral to neurology, just to be safe, and I have the appointment tomorrow (01/27/2021). I still feel residually weak, slight chest tightness, and overall feeling off/weird. Again, I do not know if this is directly related to the vaccine, but I wanted to make you aware just in case!

12/29/2020- Received the Moderna Vaccine - no pain or problems until 01/04/2021 01/04/2021- Before bedtime my injection site from the Moderna Vaccine became itchy. 01/05/2020- Woke up to a swollen arm (about 3 times the size of my right arm) and the start of a rash (the size of a softball) Was in significant pain and unable to lift my arm. I called the nurse hotline where I received the vaccine. I was told to go to the ER immediately. The ER doctor informed me that they had been seeing this and that their personal vaccine location swelled up as well but went away a few days later. ER doctor gave me Benadryl cream (I can not ingest Benadryl due to an opposite reaction, I become extremely anxious.) The ER doctor informed me that the Benadryl cream wouldn't cause the same reaction. I was sent home with the cream and a wrap. Upon arriving home my rash grew exponentially over the following days. The site became hot (even after icing it) It remained itchy and painful. 01/11/2021- Went to primary care doctor. The rash and swelling had decreased although you could still see the ring of the rash. At this point, my hand was becoming numb after doing daily activities including typing. My palm and thumb area started to turn purplish/blueish when I would type for less than 20 seconds. The doctor told me they would start to reach out to other providers and figure out how to best move forward. In the meantime, there wasn't much to do besides wait and see what happens. 01/13/2021- Woke up throughout the night due to continued pain at the injection site. Called the primary care doctor who wasn't in the office, waited for a call back from their nurse but due delayed call back and increased pain and numbness went to urgent care (which is under the same practice as primary care). The urgent care doctor performed tests regarding pinched nerve shoulder (as they believed I had a pinched nerve in my shoulder) and ordered an x-ray. The x-ray showed tissue damage but nothing else. I was not experiencing shoulder pain, although during one of the shoulder tests I found more discomfort in my left should (injection arm) than my right arm. Therefore, the primary care doctor thought I was experiencing a pinched nerve in my shoulder. 01/14/2021 - Primary care doctor called and informed me they had spoken with the infectious disease doctor in the area who informed them that they have been seeing a similar reaction amongst other people. (7 days after inject, swelling and rash) The infectious disease doctor reported they hadn't seen numbness. The primary care doctor advised me to wait 2 weeks to see how symptoms change before performing additional tests. The primary care doctor also advised me after speaking with the infectious disease doctor to not take the second shot. 01/16/2021- still experiencing issues with daily functioning. Still experiencing numbness in hand and arm. Still experiencing redness around the injection site (although much better still flairs up at moments) Side note: 01/03/2021 - Went cross country skiing, did fall backwards but did NOT fall on arm. Also confusion remains if I was supposed to report this or if the primary care doctor/ER doctor reported this, therefore, urgent care doctor told me to report this reaction.

Anaphylaxis reaction; A spontaneous report was received from a nurse concerning her co-worker, a 28 year-old female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 Vaccine and experienced anaphylaxis reaction. The patient's medical history was not provided. No relevant concomitant medications were reported. On 23 Dec 2020, prior to the onset of the event, the patient received the first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 23 Dec 2020, within five minutes of vaccine administration, the patient experienced anaphylaxis reaction. The patient had symptoms of throat tightness, dizziness, nausea, weakness, and increased heart rate. Treatment for the event included an epinephrine pen On 29 Dec 2020, the nurse reported that the patient was still having some of the symptoms, including dizziness, nausea, and weakness. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the event was not reported. The outcome of the event, anaphylaxis reaction, was considered not resolved. The reporter assessed the event, anaphylaxis reaction, as related to Moderna's COVID-19 Vaccine.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 28 year old female patient, who experienced a serious unexpected event of anaphylactic reaction. The event occurred apparently 5 min after first dose of mRNA-1273 (Lot# unknown) vaccine administration. She was treated with epinephrine pen. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

28 2021-03-11 gait inability, impaired driving ability I am twenty-eight years old, young, healthy active girl. I have always been into fitness and yoga. I... Read more
Close
I am twenty-eight years old, young, healthy active girl. I have always been into fitness and yoga. I live a generally healthy lifestyle. I have been a singer, a dancer, and a flight attendant! I decided sign up for the COVID-19 vaccine in order to help our world fight against this pandemic. I wanted to protect my family and friends to eradicate this virus once and for all. It was with no hesitation did I jump at the opportunity to get this vaccine when it became available to me on February 12th, 2021 at the Convention Center. As soon as I received my shot I proudly posted my photo with tears in my eyes letting the world know that we were one human closer to a COVID-19 free world. I was Moderna proud. My entire family had already received their Moderna vaccines because I come from a family of nurses, but none of them had experienced any side effects. I was confident I would be in the clear after their clear symptom free vaccine. Immediately following my vaccine my arm was a little sore, as expected. However, I did experience fatigue and mild leg cramps in my calves. One very odd symptom was that I could taste the vaccine in my mouth, like a metallic, strange taste, which I reported to my family, but everyone just laughed it off. The leg cramps went away after a day or two as well as the taste, but the fatigue continued throughout the week. I felt these symptoms were pretty average. I signed up for the V-Safe reporting system and put in my report and thought nothing of my initial vaccine symptoms. Things took a very strange turn on the morning of February 20th, 2021 at about 10am. I woke up and my face was numb, tingling all over, twitching in different parts of my face pretty severely and uncontrollably. By 4pm the tingling moved into both of my arms and hands and by 5pm it moved into both of my legs. Shortly after the cramping and twitching began in both of my legs and I lost the ability to walk, lift my legs, and just the ability to feel my legs at all. I could not walk. Obviously concerning, I thought I was originally having a reaction to a medication I had been taking for over a year called, Topamax, a nerve pain medication which can cause numbness and tingling as a side effect. I called my prescribing physician and he immediately ruled out the possibility of a reaction to this medication due to the length of time I had been on this medication, that I had not missed a dose, I had not increased or decreased the dose, and I had not experienced a reaction like this in the time that I had been taking the medication. He recommended I keep an eye on my symptoms and go to an emergency room if things worsen. Overnight, my symptoms remained the same. I woke up on Sunday, February 21st, 2021 and I still could not walk, I could not feel my legs. My legs were still twitching and cramping. My face was still numb and tingling, but the twitching had stopped in the face. My hands had stopped tingling. At this point my mother who is a nurse suggested that I call Moderna, the vaccine provider, to report a possible side effect of the vaccine. Upon contacting Moderna, the company thought that it could possibly be a reaction between the Topamax medication and the vaccine, but they had no current information about these two having any interactions. They thanked me for reporting and told me to go to an emergency room if my symptoms continued or worsen. Throughout the day on Sunday, February 21st, my symptoms remained. I was able to get to my feet, but I walking like a newborn baby giraffe or as my mother described, like a 105 year old woman. I was unable to feel my legs completely, lift them, move them without lifting them with physical help of my arms moving them. At this point on Sunday night I decided to contact my Primary Care Physician. She noted that this sounded similar to Guillain-Barre and that I sound immediately go to an Emergency Department before the symptoms get any worse. It was late on a Sunday night and I was unable to drive myself, so I waited. Overnight on Sunday into Monday I began experiencing light flashes in my eyes, heart races, lower back pain, and worsening cramping in my legs. I knew that I needed to seek treatment in an emergency room. On Monday, February 22nd, 2021 I was taken to the Emergency Room Department. They conducted blood work and a physical examination, but did not want to proceed with any MRI?s or CAT scans. The ER the doctors were baffled. They could not figure out what was causing my paralysis other than the vaccine was the only new thing that had been introduced to my body, but they could not verify or diagnose anything. They let me go with a referral to neurology. While we were sitting in the ER my cousin, a nurse anesthetist at another local hospital, called my mother who was with me with some very alarming news. Her co-worker, had experienced the same symptoms back in December and was just going through recovery after his first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. He was told by the CDC there had been 19 reported cases through the CDC where after the first dose of the vaccine people have reported numbness, tingling, and the lose of the ability to walk after receiving the first dose of the mRNA vaccine, both Moderna and Pfizer. Her co-worker was also in the same age range as myself, very healthy, young, active. He was officially diagnosed with Transverse Myletis. He has taken a full two months to regain the ability to walk and still has numb patches on his legs. He walks very slowly, but is walking. He returned to work, but cannot return to his normal life working out and being active because he does not have the strength. He was told not to get the second dose of the vaccine. There are unreported cases in this area by physicians who do not know where to turn with this information. It is hard to link these symptoms and cases because they are so obscure, but these same symptoms are occurring with those who have also had COVID-19. When I was being seen for an EMG test of my legs the physician performing the test said to us, ?I have a patient who received the vaccine and has the symptoms, maybe I should report it!?. My Grandmother?s physician just last week just sent a patient of hers with the same symptoms to neurology. I think this uncommon side effect is more common than is being reported and no one knows where to turn with the information. I finally got into the head of Neurology. I was told, ?it?ll probably get better?, basically saying that they don?t know what they can do and they are at a loss for knowing what this is and why this is happening to people after the first dose of the mRNA vaccine. Doctors don?t have answers and the vaccine companies aren?t offering information to help link these side effects together. The physician told me not to proceed with the second dose of the vaccine due to neurological side effect that I have had. I should benefit from the first dose and it is not safe for me to get the second dose from this side effect. I was unable to walk for weeks since this began on Feb. 20th. It is just now that this week I am slowly able to move my legs, but they are still very numb and heavy. I haven?t been able to drive or live my normal life. I cannot use stairs, walk long distances, stand for very long periods of time. I am twenty-eight years old and I walk like an eighty year old woman, wobbly. I have reported my case to CDC, V-SAFE, Moderna. The CDC said they would be in contact with me due to my report of extreme adverse side effects via the V-SAFE report, but I have not heard anything from them as of today. These are the uncommon side effects that need to be heard and reported. I don?t know why they are being ignored because I have been left without answers and without hope.

29 2021-01-25 dizziness Dizziness; Blood pressure 140/98; Pulse 123; Nausea; Numbness to her body; Chest tightness; Abdomina... Read more
Close
Dizziness; Blood pressure 140/98; Pulse 123; Nausea; Numbness to her body; Chest tightness; Abdominal discomfort; Felt like she was going to pass out; Developed blotchy skin to chest and neck area within minutes of injection; Heart racing; Weakness; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning a 29-year-old, female patient who experienced numbness, chest tightness, abdominal discomfort [Abdominal discomfort], felt like she was going to pass out, blotchy skin to chest and neck area [Rash macular], racing heart [Palpitations], weakness [Asthenia], dizziness [Dizziness], blood pressure 140/98 [Increased blood pressure], pulse 123 [Tachycardia] and nausea [Nausea]. The patient's medical history included asthma and there were no known drug allergies. Additionally, it was noted that there was no history of anaphylaxis. Concomitant product use included cetirizine and ibuprofen. On 22-Dec-2020, a short time prior to the onset of the symptoms, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot# 011J20A}) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. Following vaccination, the patient immediately developed numbness to her body, chest tightness and abdominal discomfort. She remained alert and oriented but voiced concern that she felt like she was going to pass out. She developed blotchy skin to the chest and neck area within minutes of injection. Her vital signs included blood pressure of 140/98 and a pulse of 123. She was given water to drink which she tolerated well. She continued with symptoms of nausea, blotchy skin, heart racing and weakness. Dizziness was also reported. She was taken to the Emergency Room. Treatment for the event included epinephrine, methylprednisolone sodium succinate, diphenhydramine and lorazepam. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not provided. The outcome of the events was reported as recovered.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 29 year-old, female patient with medical history of asthma, who experienced events of numbness, chest tightness, abdominal discomfort, felt like she was going to pass out, blotchy skin to chest and neck area, racing heart, weakness, dizziness, nausea, blood pressure of 140/98 and pulse of 123. The events occurred immediately after the first and last dose of mRNA-1273 vaccine administration. The patient was taken to the Emergency Room and recovered after receiving epinephrine, methylprednisolone sodium succinate, diphenhydramine and lorazepam. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded and the events are assessed as possibly related.

31 2021-03-15 impaired driving ability I was expecting to get the common side effects after my second dose, getting sick for a day about 12... Read more
Close
I was expecting to get the common side effects after my second dose, getting sick for a day about 12 hours after the 2nd dose. I did not get sick the next day, I just had the regular big red sore bump at the injection site. However, slightly more than a week after my 2nd dose, I started to experience double vision. Not blurry vision, but double vision, with one image on top of the other, both clear. At first it didn't bother me much, it was mostly happening in the mornings and in the evenings. Then suddenly, between the dates of 2/25 and 3/1, I started experiencing the double vision much more intensely and earlier in the day. It was not safe for me to drive, and it bothered me a lot, causing headaches and extreme nausea, I found myself going to bed at 6pm because I didn't want to be awake and deal with the side effects. I saw an Ophthalmologist (Dr.) about the problem (not realizing it was a COVID-19 vaccine side effect) who diagnosed me with cranial nerve 4 palsy in the left eye. I had to notify my job that I was unable to drive and that effected my work. Furthermore it was extremely stressful not knowing the cause or prognosis, and the worry over the medical costs for test and lab work. Since 3/2, the condition has been improving. There have been no other changes to my lifestyle or health that could account for this, other than receiving the COVID-19 vaccine. People need to know about the possibility of horrible side effects like this, it's worse when you don't know what's causing it or the prognosis.

Close
I have asthma that is primarily seasonal or exercise- induced. About 2 days after the vaccination, I experienced asthma symptoms that lasted for about 5 days. This was not related to exercise, humidity, or seasonal allergies- I woke up struggling to breathe on day 3 after the vaccine. I had shortness of breath, wheezing, resulting lightheadedness, and some dry coughing. Symptoms were worst first thing in the morning and at night. I am still experiencing some lingering difficulty breathing 10 days out from the vaccine, but no wheezing. It is very likely that I had COVID-19 in early February 2020, before testing was available in the here (My coworker returned from abroad very ill; another coworker and I became sick shortly after, and she lost her sense of taste and smell. I experienced low grade fever, intense nausea, diarrhea, shortness of breath, and extreme fatigue. The fatigue lasted for about one month.) Following this illness, I saw a sharp increase in my asthma symptoms for about 6-7 months, which gradually tapered off. Again, there was no other trigger for these symptoms such as exercise or humidity. It seems likely that I contracted COVID-19, which damaged my lungs in some way, and that the vaccine has resulted in irritating or "re-activating" that damage at a lesser intensity.

About 3-4 hours after receiving my second dose of vaccine on 1/30/21, I began to experience side effects including headache, myalgias, and fatigue (which I had also experienced with the first dose of vaccine). I had no nausea or vomiting until around 8-9 pm on 1/31/21. At that time I began to have severe nausea and had 1-2 episodes of emesis before falling asleep. I woke up around 3 am and had another episode of emesis. This continued every 15-30 minutes. I was unable to keep any fluids down as a result. After a couple of hours of this I became lightheaded and began to experience abdominal pain after repeated retching. Sometime between 6 am and 7 am I called 911 and was connected to nursing line. I was advised to go to the emergency department. After vomiting another 2 times I called 911 again and asked for an ambulance to be sent. I vomited again in the ambulance before arrival. Once in the ED I was examined, found to be tachycardic, and started on 1L of IV fluids. I was informed lab tests were being drawn, including pregnancy test, urinalysis, CBC, CMP, and toxicology screen. I was given one dose of Zofran IV. Nausea began to subside, and I was able drink fluids without nausea or vomiting. I was informed that lab tests were unremarkable. Another 1L of IV fluids had been started, but I was disconnected after maintaining PO intake and eventually discharged around 12 pm.

Patient presented for Covid-19 vaccine clinic. She did report a previous reaction to influenza vaccine, but she premedicated with benadryl for that. She did not premedicate for covid vaccine. Approximately 20 minutes after her vaccination, she was observed in the post vaccine waiting area and stated that she was a bit dizzy and tickling in her throat. In addition, she had an itchy rash on her left forearm, the side in which her vaccine was given. She was escorted to the nearest exam room. There, she began to have nearly non-stop coughing to the point of gagging. She was given epi 0.3mg im with some improvement of symptoms. Continuous monitoring showed oxygen sats in the upper 90s, BP was in the 150s systolically. She was given 50 mg of Benadryl orally. At that point, patient was taken to the procedure room via wheelchair. After approximately 30 minutes, the ticking sensation in the throat returned and patient was having more difficulty breathing. Another epi 0.3mg im was given, along with pecid 40 mg po. 125 mg of Solumedrol was given IV, with saline lock left in place. After 20 minutes, patient again was having difficulty. Another epi 0.3mg was given and EMS activated. While awaiting EMS, an albuterol neb was given. EMS activated ALS. Patient left facility in stable condition, transported to hospital. Pt received another 0.3mg of epi im enroute to hospital. Pt was in good condition at hospital and discharged to home. Pt returned to ER the following day with c/o cough, neb and prednisone given and discharged home. Pt returned to ER again on 1/2/21 with c/o elevated BP 170/80's. Pt presented to clinic on 1/4/21 with continued elevated bp 170/110, and shortness of breath.

32 2021-01-07 dizziness At 7:10am yesterday 1/7/21 I received the covid vaccine. Immediately my lips went numb, and my left ... Read more
Close
At 7:10am yesterday 1/7/21 I received the covid vaccine. Immediately my lips went numb, and my left arm and hand went numb. I waited at the hospital for 15 minutes and then attempted to drive home. I got about 2 blocks away and noticed my face was numb all the way from my chin to my nose. I went back into work into employee health and let them know. They called the pharmacist who instructed me to go to the ER. While walking to the ER I began to have difficulty breathing, and throat tightness. They called a rapid response alert and I was taken on a stretcher to the ER. I felt dizzy, nauseous and the numbness to my face was from my mid neck up to the top of my hairline at the top of my face. My left hand and arm were still numb. When they took my vitals I was hypertensive BP approximately 155/86, I was also tachycardia HR 104-110. EKG was abnormal-sinus tachycardia HR 104, and probable left atrial enlargement. I began to have severe chills/shaking for approximately 1 hour. I was given 1 liter of normal saline IV, Benadryl 25mg IV, and Zofran 4mg IV. After inspection by the doctor my throat was not swollen, or closing so an epi pen was not administered. My oxygen saturation remained above 91%. After 3 hours of being monitored in the ER my numbness to my face started to improve so I was discharged home. Labs were taken in the ER and my potassium was 3.1, calcium was 8.1. The day prior at my primary care doctors office labs were taken and all my labs were normal including my potassium and calcium. My primary care physician believes the low electrolytes the day of the reaction were due to the reaction to the vaccine. I also had a repeat EKG today (1/8/21) the day after the reaction at my primary cares office and it was normal sinus rhythm with no abnormalities. Vitals were all within normal limits. Today (1/8/21) approximately 36 hours after the vaccine administration I have mild numbness to my face as well as moderate body aches. My primary care physician believes I should not have the second dose of the covid vaccine as she fears I would have a anaphalactic reaction.

I am writing to you in regards my Moderna adverse reaction. I got your information from a small Facebook group that?s going through the same issues as me. On 1/31/21, I received my first shot of Moderna. I was told to stay 30min because I have a Sulfa allergy. I also received a flu shot 3 weeks prior. After 15 min I started to feel tingling in my face and throat tightness. As time passed, I started to feel like I couldn?t breathe at one point. As I continued to have issues breathing and started getting nauseous and lightheaded, they informed a nurse to look over me. The nurse had a student nurse do my vitals manually. She gives out standard numbers 60 heart rate and 120/80 blood pressure. My normal blood pressure is elevated in 130-140/80-90. I had to be picked up due to feeling unwell. I went home took Tylenol and slept. The next few weeks I kept feeling zaps of sharp pain in my chest area. On the 12th day after the vaccine, I had a panic attack. The panic attack started with a sharp pain in my neck and when I inhaled it hurt. I got heart palpitations and again felt like I couldn?t breathe. I never suffered from a panic attack, so we called 911. The EMTs came my blood pressure was 200s/100s and elevated heart rate (sorry don?t remember exact numbers). It was suggested I go to the ER since my numbers were high. In the ER I told the doctor about my vaccine incident. They got blood work done and she decided to do a CT scan and X-ray since something was elevated ( I don?t remember what was elevated. I am working on getting that info). My EKG, CT scan and X-ray all came out fine. I was then diagnosed with panic disorder. I was sent home and after a few hours I started to feel an internal tremor. I describe the tremor as having a cell phone on vibrate its usually is in my lower abdomen to pelvic area. My blood pressure kept spiking up into 180-190/80-100. I kept reaching out for help by going to ER once more, 3 urgent care visits and my primary. No one could help me, and I kept getting labeled as having panic/anxiety disordered. My primary doctor said I could be having adverse reaction to the vaccine, but I just have to wait it out. The internal tremor I feel constantly and sometimes it?s in my chest. I have muscle twitching, tingling in my lower limbs, muscle pain, and blood pressure spikes. I do feel like my symptoms cause anxiety because ill have these spells where I feel adrenaline running through me which will cause anxiousness. My blood pressure is getting better, but I still have spikes and have had another panic attack. I have been on Lexapro 5mg and gabapentin 300mg 3x a day for 5 weeks. During that time, my symptoms have not improved. I will be getting off the medication soon. I never had any of these issues prior. I don?t drink, smoke or do any drugs besides the medication prescribed. On 3/30/21, I reached out to my psychiatrist again and went into more detail about everything and she said she believes me about the vaccine side effects. She recommended I go back to my primary care doctor and ask to be referred to UCSD covid long haulers study to see if they can help me. I wanted to share my information to see if it might be help to your research. Thank you for your time

I still felt very weak but the dizziness had subsided. My fingers were also very cold. I laid down at home and around 6:45 PM, my cheek was still tingling, so I went back to the clinic. They sent me over to the ER. Everything came back normal, except my blood pressure was still elevated in the 140s/90s and the doctor stated I'd had a mild adverse reaction. When I got home, I went to bed. While I was in bed, I noticed my mouth area felt slightly numb. I went to bed and felt tired, but normal, in the morning. On 12/31/2020 and 1/1/2020 I experienced very bad arm pain that kept me up at night. I experienced a heaviness and throbbing sensation. It was very hard for me to move from side to side while laying down at night. During the day, the pain felt moderate, but at night was very severe. Over-the-counter pain medication helped some. The pain subsided after 2-3 days. One week after the vaccine, on 1/6/2021, I noticed pain at the injection sight again. On the night of 1/6/2021, the pain was severe again. I couldn't rotate from side to side without extreme pain and heaviness, and also felt the heaviness in my chest plate (not heart, but the bone of my chest). It kept me up most of the night. In the morning, the pain subsided to a mild pain. I applied heat and took ibuprofen the night of 1/7/2021 and noticed an improvement of pain.

1/23/2021 - The first Moderna vaccine. I had flu like symptoms, which included fatigue, muscles aches, muscle spasms, joint aches, chills, and shortness of breath for 2-3 days afterward. 2/20/2021 - The second Moderna vaccine. The side effects were much worse, including muscle aches, abdominal pain, back pain, headache, nausea, chills, fatigue, and shortness of breath. I also found myself limping. 2/21, 2/22, 2/23 - I rested and stayed home from work. Most of my symptoms had improved by the evening of the 23rd, and I felt like the shortness of breath was also improving if I took it easy. 2/24 - I went to work where the shortness of breath became much worse after working for a couple of hours. I began to get dizzy, and my hands and feet were cold and tingling. The school nurse checked my temperature (which was normal) and oxygen levels (99%). I was sent home and told to take another day or two off. I was fine if I was sitting still and doing nothing, but talking caused me to become winded. Walking and exertion of any kind caused me to become winded. Once winded, it would take 15 minutes of sitting still to get my breathing back under control. Then I would be hit by a wave of fatigue. Also, when my breathing was bad, I walked with a limp. 2/25 - I went to the shortness of breath was still bad. They were concerned. They took a chest x-ray (which came back clear), did blood work (which was normal), and gave me a Rapid Covid test (which was negative). My oxygen levels were at 99%. They prescribed a 6 day pack of MethylPREDNISolon. If I was not better by Saturday, they wanted me to return. They also did a PCR test (this came back negative on 2/28). 2/26 - The steroid did not help, and by the evening, I was worse. I went to the ER . The doctors there were concerned about a pulmonary embolism. They did blood work (which was normal), a chest x-ray (which came back clear), and an EKG (which was normal). My vitals were good, though my blood pressure was high for me (113/64). The doctor told me to continue the steroid pack and prescribed an albuterol inhaler. I was directed to contact a pulmonary specialist on 3/1 if symptoms did not improve. The doctor wrote a note for me to work from home through 3/5. 3/1 - The shortness of breath did not improve. I almost passed out while driving after I picked up my two small children from school. I could not catch my breath in the car and started to get lightheaded. When I parked, I stayed in the car huffing and puffing for several minutes. I was seeing spot, was dizzy, and my hands and feet were tingling. When I climbed out of the car, my legs buckled beneath me. I was able to grab onto the car and not fall. I had some really bad breathing episodes between 3/1-and 3/3. At these times, the breathing was so rough, that I couldn?t even talk. It would take 30 minutes or more of sitting still for me to be able to bring my breathing under control. 3/3 - Appointment with Pulmonary Specialist. I had an appointment He ruled out asthma, as the inhaler and steroid were both ineffective. He considered anxiety, but the problem was clearly not a panic or anxiety attack. (I have experienced those before and know the difference.) He ruled that out. He ran a pulmonary function test (which was normal) and a CT scan with contrast (which was normal). The doctor wrote a note for me to work from home through 3/10. 3/4 and on - My breathing was better some days than others. The less energy I exerted, the better I did. If I did too much one day, my breathing would be worse the next day. 3/7 - Ajovy injection. I was past due for this monthly injection. Once injected, I had an allergic reaction to it for the first time ever (this was the 7th time I used it). A few minutes after the injection, the injection area had a rash and was itching like crazy. I put ice on it and took benadryl. It was fine by the next morning. 3/9 - Appointment #2 with Pulmonary Specialist. The specialist was not sure what the problem was with my breathing. I was the first patient with these vaccine side effects that he had seen. He scheduled more tests and said he wanted to read more literature. He wrote a note for me to work from home through 4/6.

Patient did not experience any of these symptoms   She is 18 weeks pregnant. No complications with pregnancy.

Shortness of breath; Tingling; Numbness of body, face, neck; Tachycardia at 144; Palpitation; Elevated BP at 140/90; Chest tightness; Dizziness; Flushing of face; A spontaneous report was received from a physician, who was a 34-year-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced numbness of body, face, and neck, tingling, tachycardia at 144, palpitation, elevated blood pressure (BP) at 140/90, chest tightness, shortness of breath, dizziness, and flushing of face. The patient's medical history was not provided. No relevant concomitant medications were reported. On 27 Dec 2020, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 025J20-2A) intramuscularly for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 27 Dec 2020, three to four minutes after receiving the mRNA-1273 vaccine, the patient experienced numbness of body, face, and neck, tingling, tachycardia at 144, palpitation, elevated BP at 140/90, chest tightness, shortness of breath, dizziness, and flushing of face. The patient reported the elevated BP was not her usual blood pressure. She underwent an electrocardiogram (EKG)unknown results and was given oxygen for the events. No other treatments were administered. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. The outcome of the events, numbness of body, face, and neck, tingling, tachycardia at 144, palpitation, elevated BP at 140/90, chest tightness, shortness of breath, dizziness, and flushing of face, was considered resolving.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 34 year old female patient, who experienced a serious unexpected event of hypoesthesia and paraesthesia and non serious unexpected events of dyspnea, tachycardia, palpitations, blood pressure increased, chest discomfort, dizziness and flushing. The event occurred within 3-4 min after first dose of mRNA-1273 (Lot# 025J20-2A) vaccine administration. The patient was treated with oxygen and no medication was administered. Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Vaccine administered around 5:30pm Thursday, January 7th. Severe site pain within the first few hours of receiving vaccine, lasting about 48 straight hours. Within 8 hours of receiving the vaccine, my entire body began to ache and by the next morning I could hardly get out of bed due to the pain in my muscles. They felt like they had tightened or seized up. I could not take a step without wincing. Body chills came next, though I was unable to get out of bed to get my thermometer from the bathroom. By Saturday morning, I had more range of motion in my extremities, but it was not until Sunday evening that I could lift my left arm (the one the received the inoculation) over my head. There was a red, circular non-irritating rash surrounding the site of injection for 5 days following injection. I have no allergies to any medications, but did test positive for the Covid virus on March 18th, 2020. I realize my body's reaction was a normal physiologic response to the antibodies my body created within the last 9 months, however I am an otherwise healthy 34 year old female and wanted to report my experience because I could not find evidence that anyone else has had the same experience following the first dose of the covid vaccine.

On day 2, the nausea started and I vomited twice- the night of day 4 and morning of day 5. Intense headaches with light sensitivity were present from the night of day 3 through day 6. These felt like extreme migraines. These, combined with nausea and arm pain, prevented/interrupted my sleep. I also had loose stools on days 2 and 4.

Became unresponsive; Looked like having a seizure; Felt light headed; BP extremely low; Profusely sweating; Heart rate extremely low; A spontaneous report was received from a pharmacist, concerning a 35-year-old female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced felt light headed, became unresponsive, looked like having a seizure, BP extremely low, heart rate extremely low, and profusely sweating. The patient's medical history, as provided by the reporter, included high blood pressure. Products known to have been used by the patient, within two weeks prior to the event, included hydrochlorothiazide/lisinopril. On 29 Jan 2021, five minutes prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot Number: 025L20A) intramuscularly in the right arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 29 Jan 2021, the patient felt light-headed five minutes after receiving the vaccine. He then became unresponsive but was breathing and had a pulse. The reporter stated it looked like the patient was having a seizure; his eyes rolled upward, his left arm shook, and he did not respond to touch or voice. It was reported that 911 was immediately called and responded within a couple of minutes. The patient's blood pressure and heart rate were extremely low, and he was profusely sweating. The reporter stated that the patient came to and still felt very light-headed. The patient was then taken to the emergency department. Medical tests and laboratory results were unknown, but the reporter stated that a magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) was possibly performed. No treatment information was provided. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not provided. The outcome for the events, became unresponsive and looked like having a seizure, were resolved on 29 Jan 2021. The outcome for the events, felt light headed, BP extremely low, heart rate extremely low, and profusely sweating, was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 35-year-old, female, with medical history of high blood pressure, who experienced a serious unexpected event of syncope, seizure, and non-serious unexpected events of dizziness, hypotension, hyperhidrosis, and heart rate decreased. The events occurred 1 day (5 min) after mRNA-1273 (Lot# 025L20A). Treatment information was not provided. Concomitant medications included: hydrochlorothiazide/lisinopril. Based on temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Additional information has been requested.

36 2021-01-25 dizziness Full anaphylactic shock; Hives; Low blood pressure; Dizziness; Stuffy nose; Bad headache; Nausea; A ... Read more

Full anaphylactic shock; Hives; Low blood pressure; Dizziness; Stuffy nose; Bad headache; Nausea; A spontaneous report was received from a healthcare facility staff member who was a 36-year-old, female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 Vaccine, and who developed full anaphylactic shock, nausea, hives, low blood pressure, dizziness, bad headache, and stuffy nose. The patient's medical history included a latex allergy and pregnancy. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On 06-Jan-2021, approximately 30 minutes prior to the onset of the symptoms, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (LOT 01122019) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. The patient received her Moderna vaccine on 06 Jan 2021 at noon. She reported that approximately 30 minutes after receiving the vaccine, she went into full anaphylactic shock. She stated that the reaction began with nausea. She then developed hives, got low blood pressure, and was dizzy. She was taken to the hospital. There, she received two rounds of epinephrine along with diphenhydramine and famotidine. She was released that same day from the hospital once she stabilized. On 07-Jan-2021, a full 24 hours after receiving her vaccine, she experienced another anaphylactic reaction. She stated that the reaction happened exactly like it did on 06 Jan 2021 and presented with all the same symptoms. Patient injected herself with the epinephrine pen that she had at home as soon as the symptoms started. In addition to the anaphylactic reactions she experienced, patient reported that she had a bad headache since receiving the vaccine as well as a stuffy nose that comes and goes and coincides with hives. As of 10 Jan 2021, she stated that the flare ups had finally subsided, however, she continued taking diphenhydramine and famotidine as prophylaxis for anaphylactic reaction. Treatment for the event included epinephrine, diphenhydramine, and famotidine. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events, full anaphylactic shock, nausea, hives, low blood pressure, dizziness, bad headache, and stuffy nose, was not provided. The events, full anaphylactic shock and low blood pressure were considered resolved on 07 Jan 2021. The events, nausea, hives, and dizziness were considered recovered/resolved on 10 Jan 2021. The outcome of the events, bad headache and stuffy nose, were not reported.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 36-year-old female patient with medical history of latex allergy, who received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot 01122019), and who experienced the serious unlisted event of Anaphylactic shock, the non-serious listed events of Headache and Nausea, and the non-serious unlisted events of Urticaria, Hypotension, Dizziness, and Nasal congestion. Based on the current available information and temporal associon between the use of the product and the onset of events starting on the day of vaccination, a causal relationship cannot be excluded and the events are considered possibly related to the vaccine.

36 2021-02-07 dizziness Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine EUA I received the 2nd shot of the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine around 9:25 am... Read more
Close
Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine EUA I received the 2nd shot of the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine around 9:25 am on 2/5/2021, after about 10 minutes I became hot and lightheaded. Immediately after that I started getting tingling and numbness bilaterally in my hands and fingers with a heavy sensation. My heart also started racing. The nurses put me in a wheelchair and escorted me upstairs to the ER. In transit my face and throat/neck started getting tingling as well. By the time we reached the ER waiting room (9:42 am) I got the shakes/chills and was very cold. I continued having the shakes for several minutes. By the time I was brought back into the triage area (9:50 am) my legs from the shin to feet bilaterally started going numb/tingly as well. I started having a cyclical reaction. I would shake/have the chills for about 5 minutes (without any tingling/numbness in extremities), after that I would get a full body flushing sensation with feeling of lightheadedness and nausea, followed by numbness/tingling in both hands and feet. Then the cycle would repeat itself for several hours. I continued to have a heavy sensation of my hands and feet until about 10:15 am. After that the heaviness sensation did not accompany the tingling/numbness that persisted. I was hooked up to IV fluids and IV benadryl at 10:45 am. By 12:30 I finally stopped getting the chills/shaking sensation but I had a consistent body flushing followed by tingling/numbness in my hands and feet (mostly hands/arms) about every 5 minutes. Around 1 pm I all symptoms had stopped. The doctor said all my tests and blood work looked good. I was discharged from the hospital around 2:45 pm with instrustions to followup with primary doc or return to the ER if symptoms got worse. At 5:30 pm that evening all my symptoms came back, started with chills and then full body flushing sensation followed by tingling/numbness in both arms/hands bilaterally. I also had a hot sensation up the entire side of my left arm (injection site arm) up to my ear. I took 2 500 mg tablets of Tylenol and 2 25 mg tablets of benadryl at 6:20. By 6:40 I was starting to feel a little better with less shaking and less body flushing/tingling. Symptoms seemed gone by 7 pm. I went to bed at 9 pm and woke up around 10:30 pm to my body flushing and my hands going tingling/numb. I tried to sleep, but could not. Around 11:30 pm I took 1 500 mg tablet of Tylenol and 2 25 mg tablets of benadryl. I woke up the next morning (2/6/2021) with no numbness/tingling shaking or body flushing. I felt extremely exhausted and sore. That day my symptoms did not return. I woke up on Sunday 2/7/2021 with no symptoms, but around 8:30 am I had a lightheaded episode and hot sensation with a feeling of nausea. I then started to get tingling in my face, mouth and lips. It persisted for 2.5 hours until I decided to take Benadryl (2 25 mg tablets). about 30 minutes after taking medication the tingling stopped. It did not return.

The injection site was swollen and painful for 3 days just like the first vaccine, but the fever and full body aches accompanied by once of the worst light sensitive headache I have ever experienced lasted for 2 days. The 3rd day was interesting, my fever broke and my lower back now ached very bad and I was weak to stand. The most interesting thing that happened on the third day was a full badly rash that looked and felt like a full body sunburn. My fever had broken, but my skin was bright red and radiated heat of 101.5, but my head temp read normal 98.6 The red sunburn skin cut off dramatically at my wrists. I took pictures because it was so bizarre looking. By Wednesday morning the rash/sunburn was almost 70% gone and I was starting to feel like a normal human being again. I would like to note that I had a very mild fever 99.9 with my first vaccine shot and my arm was very sore and swollen for 3 days. I did also have a mild fever rash on my belly, back & forearms I would also like to say this was the sickest I have been in over 5+ years ( my second dose) it was no joke! 37 2021-01-27 dizziness The HCW noted w/i 1 hr of vaccination a constellation of symptoms including dizziness, disorientatio... Read more
Close
The HCW noted w/i 1 hr of vaccination a constellation of symptoms including dizziness, disorientation, and fatigue; and by 4 hrs she developed swelling LUE with pain and some swelling extending to the L neck. Over the next several days she reported marked swelling and tenderness over the triceps upper arm area; persistent swelling and pain in the neck that required cold packs for a couple days. The reaction appeared to be more pronounced and extensive akin to the Humira local reaction she would ordinarily get; the last dose of that was 4 months prior. By history, it sounds like extensive angioedema. At no point was there any pruritus, erythema, or hive or rash on any other part of the body; no respiratory compromise, stridor or wheeze; and no fever. Symptoms subsided over several days and she was well on day of her presenting for her second vaccination. The vaccinator (who is a pediatrician), an on-call allergist; and this reporter (a medical oncologist) all consulted on best approach. The allergist recommends skin testing; Humira may have a polysorbate component; and we collectively thought a contraindication to proceeding. Given the deliberation the HCW actually elected also not to proceed. We informed her that early data suggests one dose of the Moderna vaccine may confer an approximate 80% protection. She will present to EHS for further evaluation.

38 2021-01-26 dizziness Within the first 10 minutes of receiving the vaccine, my heart started racing and I began to feel di... Read more
Close
Within the first 10 minutes of receiving the vaccine, my heart started racing and I began to feel dizzy and lightheaded. I am an athlete and am used to fast cardio, racing heart, but this was not like anything I had ever felt before. I had difficulty located a nurse to help me. When someone finally saw I needed help, the nurse came over and took my blood pressure and pulse. She said my pulse was abnormally high as was my blood pressure and that I looked bad. She told me to take deep breaths and asked if it were a panic attack. I said it was not. I was able to control my breathing and stay calm and I eventually my heart rate came down. She did not offer me a place to lay down even though I felt like passing out. She told me that I should sit a little longer. Within another 10 minutes the same exact reaction happened again. At this point I told her I was a little worried as I've never had this kind of reaction before. She then took my bloood pressure and pulse again and told me to deep breathe. The pulse and blood pressure eventually came down. She asked me if I wanted water. I had water and some trail mix that I happen to have on me. I had to use the restroom, she walked me to the restroom. Once I realized I was not going to be offered any additional care, I decided to try and drive home. By the time I was home those symptoms had subsided, but I had a terrible migraine headache (Friday night). I went to bed and woke up the next morning with a small headache (Saturday morning). The migraine came back that night along with intense arm pain. The next morning (Sunday morning) after that I felt better and then later that night the migraine came back. On Monday those symptoms had subsided. I seemed to be getting better, but on Friday, January 22 (one week after the initial vaccine) my arm was burning and swollen and itched a lot. The injection site was warm to the touch and very tender. The swelling lasted until Sunday, January 24th. I finally called my physician on Monday, January 25th. I wasn't sure if I should get the second dose or not. Her nurse called me back and told me that my symptoms were not normal and that if I wanted to get the second dose I could take Benadryl ahead of time. I have not taken the second dose at this point. Today, January 27th, my arm seems to be better, but occasionally itches and I feel a sharp pain sometimes at random. My second dose is scheduled for February 12, 2021.

The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below. The patient's past medical history included Rhinitis and Sinuplasty. Concomitant products included MACROGOL 3350 (MIRALAX), COLLAGEN, BIOTIN, KERATIN (BIOTIN PLUS KERATIN) and LINACLOTIDE (LINZESS) for an unknown indication. On 14-Jan-2021 at 1:00 PM, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 14-Jan-2021, the patient experienced ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (anaphylactic reaction) (seriousness criterion medically significant), DYSPHAGIA (inability to swallow), TACHYCARDIA (fast heartbeat), DIZZINESS (dizziness), TREMOR (shakiness) and FLUSHING (felt flushed). On 14-Jan-2021, ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (anaphylactic reaction), DYSPHAGIA (inability to swallow), TACHYCARDIA (fast heartbeat), DIZZINESS (dizziness), TREMOR (shakiness) and FLUSHING (felt flushed) had resolved. In January 2021, Respiratory rate: 18 (Inconclusive) 18bpm. mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosing was delayed on an unknown date. For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments. Treatment medication included epinephrine, IV steroid and IV diphenhydramine. She waited for a full 30 minutes after vaccine and reported that all symptoms had resolved. Vitals at 01:10 were BP 118/80, Spo2 97, heart rate of 43 (up to 60 at 01:30).

39 2021-04-24 gait disturbance Patient began experiencing pain and difficulty walking on Tuesday, March 23. Later that afternoon sh... Read more
Close
Patient began experiencing pain and difficulty walking on Tuesday, March 23. Later that afternoon she was taken to an Urgent care, who sent her to the ER for evaluation. She was diagnosed with a very large blood clot in her leg, spanning from just above the knee to her groin area. They admitted her and began treating her with blood thinners. While undergoing that treatment, her heart stopped 3 times and she had to be resuscitated. They discovered a pulmonary embolism. While removing a large clot from her lungs, the doctor found that her lungs were riddled with hundreds of tiny blood clots. They also said that she was bleeding internally, very heavily, from an unknown location. In all, they gave her 20 units of blood, and none of it stayed in her veins. The doctor said it seemed to just disintegrate. At that point, her brain and organs had begun shutting down and family made the decision to remove her from life support. She passed away Thursday evening, March 25, 2021.
